  "reference": "Numerics @ a2c4dbf. Args convention (this port's own -- Percentile has no matrix/vector shape to flatten, so one is defined here): args = [data_1..data_n, k, data_is_sorted (0.0/1.0)], with n = len(args) - 2. Test_Percentiles' own 1e-2-tolerance literals are too loose for this fixture's 1e-9 target, so the `k in {0.01,0.05,0.25,0.5,0.75,0.95,0.99}` expected values were recomputed independently (Python, replicating the exact Type-7 zero-based-linear-interpolation formula on the same 69-value sample) and confirmed reproducible against the real C# Percentile by tools/verify_oracles.py; k in {0, 1} hit the trivial sorted[0]/sorted[n-1] shortcuts and match the scraped literals exactly. `p50_sorted` re-runs the k=0.5 case with the data pre-sorted and `data_is_sorted=true`, locking the sorted-input fast path against the same expected value as the unsorted `p50` case. `small_median`/`small_interp` are small hand-computable datasets exercising the odd-n exact-index case and a clean quarter-way interpolation, independent of the scraped sample.",
